{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"307b8d88-43b6-44b6-8acd-70456547a328","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process, communicates over stdin/stdout, and shows available tools, resources, and prompts.\n\n**4. Debug workflow:**\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke tools with test inputs.\n- Use the **Resources** tab to browse exposed resources.\n- Check the **Console/Logs** pane for raw JSON-RPC messages to diagnose issues.\n\n**⚠️ Important:** Your server must write MCP JSON-RPC messages to **stdout only**. Any logging or debug output should go to **stderr** (e.g., `Console.Error.WriteLine()`), otherwise the Inspector will fail to parse the protocol stream.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"592e40de-0a89-41d6-b202-bea4b80abd61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change request. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":380},"id":"a9d4c464-39e1-48f1-b49c-7e0b26086677","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:51:34.099Z","parentId":"6ce1b9f7-ff0d-4b03-b035-ff0c25869337"}
